Copyright.AdditionalInfo: USGS Florida MT survey consists of 19 long-period NIMS sites. Three wideband sites collected at the locations where NIMS data is missing, 016, 019 and 021, are also included. The long-period MT data were collected by the USGS Geomagnetism Program to complement the NSF's EarthScope USArray program in Florida. To simplify user experience, the same periods have been used, additionally augmented by shorter period transfer functions for completeness, and the sites were rotated to geographic coordinates for archiving. The final Florida TFs are a careful mix-and-match of periods and modes from various single-station (SS), remote reference (RR) and multi-station (MMT) processing configurations, and are truly a work of art. First, the longer periods were extracted from SS and RR TFs, while the shorter periods were typically best in MMT TFs. Further, TFs 001, 005, 006, 007, 011 and 016 (wideband) benefitted from a mix-and-match of modes due to a damaged electric wire in the middle of the run. The final assessment of data quality and merger is based upon comparison of conclusive transfer functions estimates calculated independently by Paul Bedrosian (PB) and Anna Kelbert (AK). The comparison comes from examination of apparent resistivity and phase for the principal impedance data as well as the tipper data. AKs processing went to longer periods (30,000 sec) by using additional decimation levels. Her processing also applies the 'standard' EarthScope period map. Impedances from PB apply less decimation levels often leading to cleaner long-period estimates (more statistical samples to average) but which only extend to 10,000 sec period. In the merged set of TFs that are archived at IRIS SPUD, PBs and AKs TFs were carefully assessed for relative quality, and the 'best' information was extracted from each. Linear interpolation to the required set of periods was performed as necessary when PBs estimates were used, taking the error covariances into account. The TFs were obtained using Fortran EMTF software by Gary Egbert, and his Matlab ArrayManager tool. The merger by period and mode, and interpolation has been performed using Matlab mttf software by Anna Kelbert. Finally, the rotation to geographic coordinates and conversion to XML for archiving was accomplished using Anna Kelbert's EMTF File Conversion Utilities (EMTF-FCU) Fortran software available at https://seiscode.iris.washington.edu/projects/emtf-fcu.
